AQUENTA WATER BILLING AND MANAGEMENT SYSTEM

Official Website Domain: https://aquenta-coop.com

PROJECT DESCRIPTION
AQUENTA is a web-based water billing and account management system designed to support the daily operations of a water cooperative. It helps office staff manage concessioner records, billing cycles, payments, and operational reports in one centralized platform.

Target users:
- Administrative staff
- Billing and collections staff
- Concessioners
- Technical support and development team


1) FEATURES

1.1 User and Access Module
- Login for Admin and Concessioner roles
- Role-based page access
- Session validation on protected pages
- Logout hardening to prevent access through browser back navigation

1.2 Concessioner Management Module
- Create and update concessioner profiles
- Manage account details, meter details, district, and status
- Maintain linked user and account records

1.3 Billing Module
- Create and update billing records
- Record previous and current meter readings
- Compute and store bill amounts, penalties, and statuses
- Manage billing periods

1.4 Payment Module
- Record payments per billing account
- Arrears-first payment distribution
- Reverse payment distribution when correction is needed
- View payment ledger and status tracking

1.5 Reporting Module
- Dashboard summary metrics
- Aging receivables
- Arrear summary
- Disconnection list
- Consumption and water-loss reporting
- Revenue and collection analytics

1.6 Contact and Inquiry Module
- Submit inquiry/contact form entries
- Admin-side retrieval of submitted inquiries


2) SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE

The system is composed of three major layers:
- Frontend: User interface in the browser
- Backend API: Business and data processing services
- Database: SQL Server storage for all records

How the system works:
1. A user enters or requests information from a page.
2. The frontend sends a request to the backend API.
3. The backend validates the request and applies business rules.
4. The backend reads or writes data in SQL Server.
5. The backend returns a response to the frontend.
6. The frontend displays the final result to the user.

Technologies used:
- Frontend: HTML, CSS, JavaScript
- Backend: ASP.NET Core Web API (.NET)
- Data access: Dapper with repository and service layers
- Database: Microsoft SQL Server


3) USAGE GUIDE

3.1 Production access
- Live website: https://aquenta-coop.com

3.2 Administrator workflow
1. Log in with admin credentials.
2. Open the required module from the sidebar.
3. Perform updates in records, billing, payment, or tariff screens.
4. Review related reports to confirm the changes.
5. Log out after completing tasks.

Common admin modules:
- Dashboard
- Billing
- Invoices
- Customer Records
- Payments
- Tariffs
- Reports

3.3 Concessioner workflow
1. Log in with concessioner credentials.
2. Review account profile and billing history.
3. Check payment history and current account standing.
4. Log out after review.


4) DATABASE STRUCTURE

4.1 Main tables
- tbl_User: user account, credentials, and role
- tbl_Concessioner: concessioner profile and account details
- tbl_Billing: meter readings, bill values, and status
- tbl_Payment: payment transaction records
- tbl_Period: billing month period ranges
- tbl_Tariffs: tariff values and settings
- tbl_District: district or area reference
- tbl_Category: concessioner category reference
- tbl_Membership: membership and discount setup
- tbl_ContactSubmission: contact and inquiry entries

4.2 Key relationships
- Concessioner -> User, District, Category, Membership
- Billing -> Concessioner, User, Period
- Payment -> Billing

4.3 Reporting database objects
The system uses SQL views and stored procedures to produce report outputs for:
- receivables and collection summaries
- delinquent and disconnection monitoring
- water consumption and water-loss computation
- account-level billing and payment insights


5) TESTING GUIDE

Current testing method:
- Manual functional testing
- API checks using Swagger
- SQL validation for procedures and report outputs

5.1 Basic functional checklist
- Admin login succeeds with valid credentials
- Concessioner login succeeds with valid credentials
- Invalid login displays the correct error message
- Billing module loads and saves records correctly
- Payment distribution and reverse distribution function correctly
- Report pages display expected data
- Logout prevents protected page reuse through the browser back button

5.2 API testing quick checks
- Open Swagger: http://localhost:5024
- Test login, billing, payment, and report endpoints

5.3 Health check
- Open: http://localhost:5024/health


6) SECURITY

Implemented controls:
- Page-level route guards for protected modules
- Cache-control headers to reduce sensitive page caching
- Back-navigation protection after logout
- Input validation in contact submission APIs

Important future enhancement recommendations:
- Password hashing and salting
- Token-based API authentication
- Stronger server-side role authorization policies


7) MAINTENANCE

7.1 Routine maintenance tasks
- Monitor system availability and API health
- Back up the database regularly
- Re-validate reports after changes
- Keep SQL scripts versioned and documented

7.2 Backup guidance
- Schedule daily incremental backups
- Schedule weekly full backups
- Test the database restore process periodically

7.3 Troubleshooting reference
- Frontend cannot load records:
  Verify that the backend is running on port 5024.

- Database connection issue:
  Verify the SQL Server instance and AQUENTA_SQL_CONNECTION value.

- Port conflict:
  Run stop-whole-system.bat and restart the services.
